tweet: It's like for most of the story, he think that he exists, and then at the end, he realizes that he's merely an actor in a play with an assigned role, and though he can walk away from the stage, but his drive to be faithful to that character is bigger than possibly saving himself.

name: Zito
tweet: It's that Oedipus unlike many of the others, sees the trap of his story when he can still save himself, or is granted the idea that he could, and still doesn't because he accepts what must happen and that he must complete his part.

name: Zito
tweet: The same thing happens to Coriolanus at the end. He rages through the entire story, being destructively himself while everyone begs him to be different. And then at the end, when he breaks character for the good of everyone. That decision leads directly to his death.

name: Zito
tweet: I remember telling a friend that when Achilles gives Hector's body back to Priam is my favorite part of the Iliad, because it reverses the story. It's the only time that Achilles does break character. When he stops raging and says so himself. And in doing so he seals his fate.

name: Zito
tweet: It's a wonderful illustration of nature and nurture working within one person. Not just determinism. External powers have already molded his possibility, and in doing so creates him, and so though he has the choice to leave the trap, he would have to stop being himself.
